{ A typical position in the Najdorf Be3 variation. White has castled queenside and started the dangerous pawn storm on the kingside. Black ideally wants to create a pawn break on the queenside but there are worries about White succeeding first. The position calls for the thematic move: }
13... g5 { The idea is pretty clear: To slow down White's expansion while also attempting to create a permanent outpost on e5 for your knight. g5 is often played as a pawn sacrifice too. See Dagur Arngrimsson - Alexander Kovchan below for an example. } 14. h4 { White's best try is to concede the e5 square but further complicate the position. } (14. fxg5?! Ne5) 14... gxf4 15. g5 { And a messy game ensues } *


