[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sicilian Najdorf Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "Bg5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/A1odpWyJ/F8dJtrZS"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.07.15"]
[UTCTime "03:08:18"]

1. Bg5 Nbd7 { Nbd7 is the modern move, which has been becoming more and more popular. e6 has always been the main line for years, but there is just so much theory in that line, it is hard to really understand fully why each move is played. Even top Grandmasters like Caruana and MVL said themselves that they have followed engine recommendations in their preparation. } 2. f4 (2. Bc4 { The second most popular move, which I find quite easy to deal with. The goal for Black here is to try to limit the power of the Bc4 with e6, b5 and a Nc5. } 2... Qb6 { Often, the best way to punish an early development of White's dark squared bishop is to attack the b2 pawn } 3. Bb3 e6 4. Qd2 Be7 5. O-O-O Nc5! { The key move in this variation! If the Bb3 ever gets dangerous, the choice to exchange is in your hands. } 6. Rhe1 h6 7. Be3 Qc7 8. f3 b5 9. Kb1 Bd7 { Flexible position here. Keeping the king in the center is fine, but if the center breaks open, such as if White sacrifices a pawn, you should flee to safety on the kingside. }) 2... Qc7 3. Qf3 h6 4. Bh4 g5!? { Following theme #1 above } 5. fxg5 hxg5 6. Bxg5 Qc5 7. Be3 Ne5 8. Qe2 Neg4 9. Bg1 Bh6 { This is the main line in a fairly theoretical variation. Black prevents White from castling long, and exerts annoying pressure for White on all sides of the board. } 10. h3 (10. Nf5 { The most logical of the discovered attacks. However, the b2 pawn is still vulnerable. } 10... Qb4) (10. a3 Qb6 { Again, the goal is to pressure the b2 pawn. Since White doesn't have the option to 0-0-0, it is quite frustrating to play. }) 10... Bf4 { White cannot capture the knight due to Rxh1. This position is extremely dynamic, but Black scores well in practice. Bg3+ is the threat, with an initiative. } *


[Event "🏆 Sicilian Najdorf Repertoire 🏆: bg5 part 2"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/nHsHvquq/gUWm6bki"]
[Date "2020.07.15"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Mr_Penings"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Sicilian Najdorf Repertoire"]
[ChapterName "Bg5 part 2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/A1odpWyJ/A7bfxPXQ"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.07.15"]
[UTCTime "03:08:18"]

1. Bg5 Nbd7 2. Qe2 { In this chapter, we will discuss the queen moves Qd2 and Qe2. Both are invitations to a sharp middlegame if White castles long. This is one of the most dynamic lines for White! I suggest studying this line in depth, as it differs from the common approach with e6. } (2. Qd2 e6 3. O-O-O b5) (2. Be2 { White could develop normally and somewhat passively. This gives no problems to Black, and I recommend the standard setup of Theme #5. } 2... Qc7 3. O-O e6 4. Kh1 b5 5. a3 Bb7 { Black is fine here. }) 2... h6 3. Bh4 g6 (3... g5?! { g5 is a bit premature here since White hasn't played f4 yet. You don't achieve the e5 outpost, and you've only overextended the kingside. } 4. Bg3) 4. f4 e5 { e5 is my suggestion here, as is the main line. Playing the usual e6 is just not fitting here since White has e5. } 5. fxe5 (5. O-O-O!? { I've seen this line before in practice. In theory, castling right away is not as strong as inserting fxe5 dxe5 first due to the d-file not being completely open, but it is still extremely sharp. } 5... exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6+ Ne5 8. fxe5 Be6 { Since the d-file isn't open, Black is actually doing well here. There is ample play on the queenside, so Black doesn't have to solely play passive defense. }) 5... dxe5 6. O-O-O! { To be frank, this line gives me the chills. I have analyzed this with Stockfish to make sure all of the lines are accurate since this is one of the most dangerous (if not THE most) lines in the Najdorf! } 6... Qc7 7. Nb3 (7. Nd5!? { Going all out with Nd5 doesn't cause a ton of harm since Black can castle kingside in time } 7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Bd6) 7... b5 8. Nd5 (8. Rxd7!? { Believe it or not, this line actually is sound! Since Nxd7 is forced (otherwise White wins the other knight as well), White gains full control over the d5 outpost, and has plenty of compensation. However, there is a forced repetition that White has (and Black should take it) } 8... Nxd7 9. Nd5 Qb8 10. Na5 Bg7 11. Qf3 O-O 12. Be7 Re8 13. Nc6 Qb7 14. Na5 Qa7 15. Nc6 Qb7 16. Na5 Qb8 { Draw by repetition 1/2-1/2 }) (8. Qf3 Bg7 9. Rxd7 { Transposes to the draw line above. Again, draw as Black should be fine. Not much else to say on how to avoid a draw without risking being worse. }) 8... Nxd5 9. exd5 Bd6 { At least the center is closed now. Black ideally is fine, but still has to be alert for tactics. } 10. Qd2 { Preventing kingside castling. } 10... f5 { Ambitious but accurate. Black truly can gain space in the center with little risk. } 11. g4 f4 { Welcome to a dynamic middlegame! } *


